`IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory by default. For large files, read the raw request body stream directly to disk:

```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable the default form body size limit
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.HasFileContentDisposition())
            continue;

        var trustedName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // avoid path traversal
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", trustedName);

        await using var fs = new FileStream(savePath, FileMode.Create);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);  // streams chunk-by-chunk, ~80KB default buffer
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
}).DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Key configuration (required for >~28MB requests):**

```csharp
// Remove Kestrel's request body size cap (default 30MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(opts =>
{
    opts.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

// Disable form size limits for the endpoint
builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = long.MaxValue;
});
```

**Why this works:**

| Approach | Memory use |
|----------|-----------|
| `IFormFile` | Buffers entire file (~2GB in RAM) |
| `MultipartReader` | Streams in small chunks (~80KB) |

**Additional tips:**

- Use `CancellationToken` on `CopyToAsync` so disconnects abort the write.
- If behind IIS/Nginx, raise their upload limits too (`maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`).
- Add `[RequestSizeLimit(2_147_483_648)]` if using controller-based endpoints instead of minimal APIs.
- Consider adding a progress callback with a custom buffer loop if you need to report upload progress.
